        <div xml:id="AN145.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">makaṭpōkkiya cevilittāy colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What the foster mother said who had let [her] daughter go.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN145.2">
            <lg type="edition">
              <l>vērmuḻu tulaṟi niṉṟa puḻaṟkāṟ</l>
              <l>ṟērmaṇi yicaiyiṟ ciḷvī ṭārkkum</l>
              <l>vaṟṟaṉ maratta poṟṟalai yō<supplied>ti</supplied></l>
              <l>veyiṟkavi ṉaḻinta vaippiṟ paiyuḷkoḷa</l>
              <l>nuṇṇiti ṉi<supplied>ka</supplied>rkkum veṇ<supplied>ñe</supplied>mai viyaṉkāṭ</l>
              <l>ṭāṉi latta<supplied>n</supplied> ta<supplied>mi</supplied>ya ḷavaṉoṭu</l>
              <l>vāḷvari poruta puṇkūr yāṉai</l>
              <l>pukarcitai mukatta kuruti vāra</l>
              <l>vuyarcimai neṭuṅkōṭ ṭurumeṉa muḻaṅku</l>
              <l>maruñcura miṟantaṉa ḷeṉpa peruñcī</l>
              <l>raṉṉi kuṟukkaip paṟantalait titiyaṉ</l>
              <l>ṟoṉṉilai muḻumuta ṟumiyap paṇṇiya</l>
              <l>naṉṉar melliṇarp puṉṉai pōla</l>
              <l>navinavaip paṭiya mātō kalimayil</l>
              <l>kuñcarak kurala kurukō ṭālun</l>
              <l>tuñcā muḻaviṟ ṟuttiyal vāḻak</l>
              <l>kūḻuṭait tantai yiṭaṉuṭai varaippi</l>
              <l>ṉūḻaṭi yotuṅkiṉu muyaṅku maimpāṟ</l>
              <l>ciṟupal kūntaṟ pōtupiṭit taruḷā</l>
              <l>teṟikōl citaiya nūṟavuñ ciṟupuṟa</l>
              <l>meṉakkurit teṉṉā ṇiṉṟaveṉ</l>
              <l>ṉamarkka ṇaññaiyai yalaitta kaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>She alone with him on a road devoid of cows, (6)</l>
                <l>in the wide wilderness of Ñemai trees that subtly shine, (5)</l>
                <l>while the golden-headed lizard on the desiccated tree, (3)</l>
                <l>in which crickets sound like the tones of chariot bells, (2)</l>
                <l>with a tubular trunk that stands completely dried, down to the root, (1)</l>
                <l>is sorrowful, in the region the beauty of which perished in the sunlight, (4)</l>
                <l>she has gone to traverse the difficult desert, they say, (10a-c)</l>
                <l>where the wound-covered elephant that fought the one with sickle-stripes (7)</l>
                <l>thunders tumultuously on the long peaks of the high summits (9)</l>
                <l>while the blood on [its] face flows over, spoiling [its face] spots. (8)</l>
                <l>Like the mastwood tree with good, soft clusters (13)</l>
                <l>made by Titiyaṉ, when [its] whole base, its ancient foothold, was cut down</l>
                <l>by Aṉṉi of great fame, in the waste lands of Kuṟukkai, (10d-12)</l>
                <l>let them suffer capital punishment, (14a-c)</l>
                <l>– the hands that slapped my mother with beautiful eyes (22)</l>
                <l>who stood there, not one to say “this is not right by me”, (21)</l>
                <l>even though [I] beat the small of [her] back painfully with a beating stick, (20)</l>
                <l>without compunction gripping the buds in the many small tresses (19)</l>
                <l>of [her, wearing her hair] in five parts, who became weak when [her] feet took one turn (18)</l>
                <l>from the boundaries of [her] father’s place, affluent (17)</l>
                <l>so that one lives with the deceptive nature of drums that do not sleep, (16)</l>
                <l>to which the bustling peacocks dance, elephant-voiced, along with the herons. (14df.)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
